Problem Statement
In a corrupted data forwarding system, each node is linked to at most one other node via a pointer. However, due to system failures, some forwarding chains may contain cycles or become disconnected.

You are given a collection of N nodes. Each node contains:

A unique identifier node_id

An integer value

A pointer to the next node by its next_id (or -1 if it points to null)

Your task is to:

Starting from a given start_id, traverse the forwarding chain using only pointer manipulations.

Recover the longest possible simple (cycle-free) chain starting from the given node.

Break cycles in-place by setting the next of the first repeating node to null.

Print the values of the nodes in the recovered chain, from the start node to the last node, space-separated.

You must not use arrays, hash maps, or sets for cycle detection — only pointer manipulation and O(1) extra memory per node are allowed.

Input Format
The first line contains an integer N — the number of nodes.

The next N lines each contain three space-separated integers:
node_id value next_id —
where:

node_id is the unique ID of the node

value is the data stored in the node

next_id is the ID of the node it forwards to, or -1 if it points to null

The last line contains an integer start_id — the ID of the starting node for traversal.

Output Format
A single line containing space-separated integers - the values of nodes in the recovered simple chain, starting from the start_id.

Constraints
1 ≤ N ≤ 10⁵

All node_ids are distinct and positive integers

All value fields are integers in the range [-10⁶, 10⁶]

next_id is either -1 or the node_id of another node in the list

Sample Testcase 0
Testcase Input
5
10 1 20
20 2 30
30 3 40
40 4 20
50 9 -1
10
Testcase Output
1 2 3 4
Explanation
Input: 5 nodes: (10,1,20), (20,2,30), (30,3,40), (40,4,20), (50,9,-1); start=10.



Create nodes, store in map by node_id.

Link nodes using next_id (-1 = null).

Traverse from start (10): 10→20→30→40→20.

Detect cycle at 20, break by setting 40’s next to null.

Print values: 1 (10) → 2 (20) → 3 (30) → 4 (40).

Ignore node 50 (not in chain).


Output: 1 2 3 4

